 <h1>To Robert Cary &amp; Company</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Gentn</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Mount Vernon 12th August 1771</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>On the 20th Ulto I wrote you fully, and Inclosed Invoices of such Goods as Mr, Miss Custis, and myself wanted; since then I have recollected some Articles which were omitted, and which I now beg may be added, and forwarded with the other Goods.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0343-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0343-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>Holsters, or Covers for a pair of Pistols (about 12 Inches long streight Measure, which I have by me) to fit the Saddle orderd in my last for GWthis to be in the newest Taste &amp; handsome</p>
<p>The like for Mr Custiss Sadle with a handsome pr of Pistols to Suit Ditto</p>
<p>A Fashe and handsome small Sword wt. Belt Swivels &amp;ca complt. for Ditto</p>
<p>A Neat Sword Belt with Swivels &amp;ca for GW</p>
<p>3 fashe Watch Keyessize of the Inclosd</p>
<p>6 More Horse Collars than were wrote for in my last</p>
<p>8 Housings for Waggon Harness</p>
<p>100 Weight of Allum</p>
<p>And, which is an Article of more consequence than all the rest to me and the principal end of my writing to you at this time, a pair of French Burr Millstones of John Cooper agreeable to the Inclosed Letter of Daniel Williamss and the Memm of William Robert my Miller thereon.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0343-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0343-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> I must through you request this Cooper to be very particular in his choice of the Stone that the whole may be of a good and even qualityI should not Incline to give any extravagent Sum for them on the one hand nor miss of getting a pair of good ones by limiting the price on the other;
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-08-02-pb-0517">[517]</span>
and therefore leave it to you to consult with the Sellar on a price that a good pair can be bought forIt will be unnecessary to add that the sooner these can be sent to me the better; Williamss Letter (which I send in hopes of Stimulating Cooper to a good choice) will shew that I have been disappointed in my first attempt and consequently must require them as soon as you can get them forwarded which I hope will be along with my Goods. I remain Gentn Yr Most Hble Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0343-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Book ]">ALB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0343-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0343-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>These goods and the millstones were shipped with Carys invoice of 3 Dec. 1771.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0343-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0343-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Neither Williamss letter nor Robertss memorandum has been found. Daniel Williams may be the Mr. Williams of Pennsylvania who sent GW a bolting cloth for his mill two years later (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-09-02-0277" class="document">William Milnor to GW, 19 Oct. 1773</a>). John Cooper may have been either the wheelwright at no. 4 Stoney Lane, Southwark, or the packer at no. 1 Bell Court, Fenchurch Street, both men by that name.</p>

</div>
